  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The purpose of this study was to compare two methods for neuromuscular monitoring,
      acceleromyography and mechanomyography for establishing the dose-response relationship and
      the potency of a neuromuscular blocking agent using rocuronium as an example. We hypothesized
      that there would be no significant difference between potencies estimated using
      acceleromyography and mechanomyography.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
